\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 Well, I still kept an interest in various aspects.  The reason
 I went to rituals was that [while] I was nonetheless interested in cultural dimensions, yeah, the sociology was important, but there had to be an exploration of some of the ways in which relationships were differentially, culturally inflected, and it was
 by looking at rituals I felt that I could get at some of that in a practiced sort of way.  And it\rquote s one of the positions at Manchester, was its emphasis on practice.  It undervalued \endash  I think, rightly, in many ways \endash 
 interviews.  It saw that, in a sense, the interview is always affected by the interviewer/interviewee relation, and so affected by the structure of the questions, which is not a good way of getting at people\rquote 
s cultural orientations, which emerge in practice itself, but when they\rquote re not, in fact, being asked.  If you ask people about their culture, you\rquote 
ll get all kinds of stereotypes, but if you look at it as being work done in particular action contexts, then you see the ambiguities, the complicated way a thing is changing and moving.  But an in
terview tends to produce static understandings, whereas practice looks at things in unfolding flow.  Hence my interest in ritual.  Ritual \endash  and this is also from the \'85 from the Manchester side \endash  if you look at ritual practices, that
\rquote s where people are un-self-consciously, in a way, working into the deep roots of certain cultural things, so they\rquote re not worrying about explaining it, or doing it, they\rquote re working with it, okay?  And a whole series of p}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11494139 ossibilities emerge from that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 So it was in looking at heal
ing rituals that I learnt a lot about Buddhism,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5913862  because these were Buddhists; }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 I learnt a lot about social relationships because they would feed into the rituals, and they still do.  Lots of social and political commentary about the nature of the social wor
ld in which people were located. The rituals, themselves, were performed in domestic space.  Women were often central but not in the sense that maybe Westerners look at it \endash  a tendered-based way \endash 
 women were central in the kinship structure, and so if you 
got sick, for example, if you were a male and got sick, in a sense, you had to be treated through a female, okay, because a female was at the centre of the web of social relations which influenced illness.  So illness was never an individual thing, it was
 already a social thing. So even the person that was the patient was, in a sense, the body through which all kinds of other people\rquote s illnesses were dealt with \endash 
 a much more complex notion of illness and the body and so forth than Western medical positions.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5913862   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
