\rquote t English.  I was totally - I was therefore regarded as not quite English and so many of the political leaders just loved my presence, I think.  And I was involved, in a little way, in forming the early ideas on the Zambian Constitutio
n.  But I was adopted, basically, so whereas other people were being restricted, I had free movement. I think I was a young kid, and they just thought it was great I was there.  So I was adopted in a sense, and so I got in very easily.  And not being Sout
h African, not being English, it was really an advantage.  That was when they were worried about spies and who knows what else, but it was fine, I didn\rquote 
t have any trouble.  In fact, lots of wonderful friends - I loved my period in Africa, and Africa was, in a sense, a much freer place than I found Sri Lanka.  Sri Lanka was very interesting, continually interests me, but there was a sense \'85 \tab 
It was a really wonderful time to be in Central Africa.  This was the end of Colonialism, full of hope, potential was everywhere, people were open, fabulous time!  I\rquote m going back to Zambia next year to do some work, so I\rquote 
m really wanting to go back.  I had a wonderful time there.  In Sri Lanka was different.  Sri Lanka, when I went there, even though it was independent, ha
d been tremendously affected by English colonial rule, and had an almost obscene respect for the English, which, as an Australian, I could never understand. Because Australians didn\rquote 
t have that much respect for the English, but Sri Lankans, unbelievable!  
I thought it almost obscene. Because, of course, it was a different system.  Africa was very egalitarian, Sri Lanka, as is India, very hierarchical, so the caste system and so forth, and somehow, the English got themselves into that under colonial rule. S
o there was a kind of worship of the English in Sri Lanka, which made it, I\rquote 
m sorry to admit, easier to work there, in a way, than it was in Zambia.  In Zambia there was this egalitarian sense, even though I was very well accepted, but people would be conti
nually worried about giving information.  In getting to work with my African friends on stuff, they really had to know why I wanted to know something, you know, so I\rquote 
d be given a grilling.  It was great fun, tremendous, it was really great fun, but you rea
lly had to work to get your information, because people were just not too convinced about me!  Whereas it was much easier to get basic information in Sri Lanka.  But, nonetheless, there was real concern, particularly when I was there, concern about Americ
a
, and the CIA. The CIA was the big thing that everyone was concerned about, but I was lucky there too, because I was sitting in a train, very early on in my research, trying to learn Singhalese, and there was this old guy sitting opposite me, in national 
