o realise that other systems that maybe outside the West, often have greater insight on certain possibly universal dimensions of human existence. One thing that looks really exotic, that I\rquote 
ve been working on for some time, is this phenomenon that is very exoticised in the West, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4001650 \lquote sorcery\rquote  and \lquote witchcraft\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 , and I\rquote m saying this is not about sorcery and witchcraft.  I go to Africa, or I go to Sri Lanka, it\rquote 
s not about what Westerners think sorcery and witchcraft is about, it\rquote s in fact a theory of the way in whi
ch human societies are constructed.  To call it witchcraft and sorcery is to miss out on much deeper philosophical assumptions which are contained in it about the way in which human social relations are constructed and are destroyed.  And so a lot of this
 stuff is missed for what is underpinning it, and fits into, in fact, a Western stereotype for prejudice.  So that\rquote s what I\rquote ve been showing. T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10897881 
hings like that.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 So the argument is both methodological, but methodological in a number of ways, and in a philosophical sense.  That is, I
