\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
I would like to ask you a bit more about them, but maybe we could come back to that? Because the thing which I was especially keen to record was an account of how you did your early research.  You see, in the interview there\rquote 
s quite a bit about how you worked in Sri Lanka, but with the early work there\rquote s just the themes, and not really a description of what the fieldwork was like, and I was wondering whether you could - I mean, shall with start with the zinc factory?  

\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10698257 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 No, my first fieldwork was not there.  When I first got to Zambia, or Northern Rhodesia as it was then, t
he method of training was really the Manchester line, which had been established at the Rhodes Livingstone Institute \endash  which is now the Institute for African Studies \endash 
 and the idea was that you should spend at least a year learning one of the local languages, and the way to learn the local language was to go off into a relatively remote area and work in that area.  And that\rquote 
s what I did.  I went up to the Bangweulu Swamp area, which was the Eastern side of the Congo Pedical (?? \endash  7.32) which reaches into Za
mbia, and worked among the Bisa.  The reason for working among the Bisa was that they were a Bemba-speaking people, and that Bemba, Chi-Bemba was the main language spoken on the Copper Belt, and in the mining towns. The idea was how we\rquote 
d learn Chi-Bemba}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10698257  by working with the Bisa lot.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
The other point about the Bisa was that they were a matrilineal people, and the group that I was being trained by at that time, were really interested in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12741912 
 what was called the \lquote matrilineal puzzle\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 , and whole matrilineal [?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12741912  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 region
] moving from East Africa through into the Congo.  So that was the logic for me going there \endash  learning the language and working with the people who had not yet been sufficiently described.  And so that\rquote 
s where I started, and then I published a short monograph on the Bisa.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1859212 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
What monograph was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 I think it\rquote s, }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 Co-Operation and Leadership}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
. Some boring title!  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
How did you do the work, though \endash  that piece of research?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
That piece of research?  That was, in those days, the idea was that you were dropped in the middle of it.  I think that happened to everyone, certainly the older generation, and in the next generation \endash  that which was me \endash 
we just went and walked in.  That was it.  And that\rquote s what we did basically. We managed to get in contact, when Judith and I were together there, we got in contact with the paramount ch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3371905 ief of the Bisa, he was called \lquote Kopa\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
, living at his village, Kopa. He then set up for us to go and study in a village of his kin about 11 miles away from the main village, and that\rquote 
s where we went, and began to interact with the local population there.  It was very strange, but it was great.  It was a beautiful part of the country, and the people were great.  We had very close relationships with people there.  That was
 the basis of my beginnings.  I enjoyed it very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
So that would be participant observation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
Of course.  I mean, what goes for participant observation?  As you probably know, it\rquote s more observation than participant!  It is casual eng
agement rather than systematic interviewing.  We were always advised to do systematic interviewing, but that never got you terribly far. But we did a fair bit of that too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 That\rquote 
s survey work \endash  systematic interviewing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
No.  The idea was that - like you\rquote re doing \endash 
 you sit down with people and have a long conversation with them about their background, their relationships, ask them questions, systematically, about the nature of lineage structures, or kinship relations and so forth.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 And I
 think you were saying, off the record, that you didn\rquote t record interviews?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 No, I didn\rquote 
t record interviews.  It was all note taking.  I was never terribly efficient at it.  The idea was that you\rquote re much more efficient after you\rquote ve come out of the fieldwork than you are actually in it.  I think it\rquote 
s more a story you tell rather than (LAUGHS) what actually happens.  But I always used to do that, which is talk to people - note in front of them, because that was one way of indicating to people that you w
ere being open, even though I was writing in English rather than the local language, but even then, the people I was working with were not illiterate \endash  and the idea was to write up mainly what you\rquote 
d encountered, in the evening, under a pressure lamp. Often difficult, and I was often tired.  But I developed my own way of working at that point, which was always analytic \endash 
 never just to write down facts, but always to write down material which I then began to analyse at the time, which is how I\rquote ve done fieldwork ever since.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
In other words, when you\rquote re making the notes, you have thematic headings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
No.  Many of my friends do it that way.  They had categories that they\rquote d put everything under.  I would, in fact, do a note of the entire context where I was working, as if I was just talking to one person.  It woul}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3371905 d be the kind of house it was; }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
what was happening around me while I was interviewing;  and then a detailed attempt to understand what the points of the interview were and where it was going, ho
w it would link up with other things. So that my notes were never organised into preliminary categories, and I never took them into categories after that, they were always }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 in toto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 , they are all together at the same time.  So I\rquote 
d index the notes later on, but that would be as far as I would go.  I wouldn\rquote 
t have categories.  And that, I discovered, was different from the way in which many of my friends did their note-taking, which was often into categories to begin with.  I didn\rquote t have those.  I think I was right not to do that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 Because it\rquote 
s closer to the raw thing do you mean?  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
Yeah, because in what context you\rquote d collected this material, and you were seeing the whole thing all the time, so that you began to see how your own understanding of things were developing over time, and often the first ones were good \endash 
 the first interpretations, on the basis of no information, were often good.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
And did you rely on some sort of key informants?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
I did, to begin with.  There was a very nice 
old lady that used to be in charge of the village, basically, she was fantastically helpful.  And then I became quite friendly with - this is a matrilineal system, so the women were extremely powerful in it, in fact, much more powerful than we were prepar
ed to talk about in those days.  I mean, we would argue \'85
 I remember, that there used to be first year courses, right, but in matrilineal society it still was the men in power, the only difference was that men had power through control over women, usually their sisters. It\rquote 
s very good for first year lectures, but also wrong.  Unfortunately I didn\rquote t collect as much as I should have done, but the people I was working with had magnificent myths of warrior females that had actually captured territory from the ne
ighbouring member who they had fought with before Pax Britannica, which indicated a much stronger position, political position, for women, than the normal matrilineal arguments that we were then working with in the 1960s.  So yeah, I think I would contest
 some of the arguments that we had in those days.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2451681\charrsid2451681 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
And then did you develop this method in any direction while you were in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose}?  Or were the other studies [using] the same kind of approach?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 No.  I had alway
s worked this way.  Always worked this way.  And to me, it paid off, so that I was always thinking analytically. It really meant that my field notes were always arguing about something, and the material would work in with that.  And it was a method I pick
ed up early on, and it worked.
