Well, now, the sort of fishermen I was working on - I did two lots of fishermen really \endash  not that I studied fishing in any great deal.  Of course, the Bengweulu people, 
the Bisa, were fishing as well as hunting, and the other ones were in Sri Lanka.  When I went to work in Sri Lanka, the community I worked with were a fisher community, but as a function of their fishing had moved into the gem and jewellery trade \endash 
 the curio business \endash  roundabout the 1870s I think, and then became extremely powerful.  Small little community became extremely powerful because they had travelled the British Empire.  I don\rquote 
t think there were any limitations on movement in the British Empire until about the 1920s or 1930s \endash  I think that\rquote 
s when limitations came.  But in that period, the Singhalese from the South, the fishing Singhalese, had moved into the gem and jewellery business, and had got everywhere in the world and established jewellery shops.  So they became extremely powerful 
\endash  not just in economic terms, but also in educational and political terms. They were highly influential in the post-Independence and the period leading up to Independence, a period of the growth of Sri Lanka.  
