ll. He was moving away from an over-institutionalised notion on things, and so it was he, following, I think, another companion of his \endash  John Barnes \endash 
 and influenced by some of the work done in South Africa, particularly by Philip Meyer, and he was really 
interested in developing network analysis, which he did.  And he had a group of students - me, David Boswell, Peter Harris-Jones, a few others - and so he was trying to build up h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4091533 is position on social networks.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 He was attracted to social networks because 
it was a move away from institutional analysis, away from over-emphasising systems as against the way in which people, themselves, were developing their relations.  He was, although very respectful of Max Gluckman, also critical \endash  as all}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2507492  students are, I suppose \endash  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 he didn\rquote 
t like these straight dichotomies of urban/rural, and saw, in networks, a way in which you could look at the way in which relationships crossed over, and didn\rquote t restrict themselves to any one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16151758  particular form.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 So that\rquote s how I got into i
t.  He asked me to try and do some work on these lines.  I then proceeded to work on the interaction of stuff that I was doing, in fact, the kind of network stuff that I developed was really an industrial organisation type of small group analysis. That
\rquote s what I was doing, and that\rquote 
s what I was influenced by when I went and looked at what was coming out at that time in the journals.  And I did it in a very detailed way, along the lines that Mitchell wanted it to be done, because they were interested not just in the rel}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8722711 ation, but in what they called \lquote the content of relations\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
 - what people were engaged with in their relations.  They wanted depth in the understanding of relations rather than just a notion of links. So I collected that kind of material, and then
 used it predictively to work out the outcome and process of various kinds of conflicts and so on.  \tab 
So that interested Mitchell, I think, to a great extent, because he was not just interested in network analysis, he was also, at the same time, wanting to 
mathematise certain dimensions of sociological understanding. They thought they could mathematise the development of social relations and the nature of their effect on certain projects.  And at that time I was collecting that material, there was a develop
ment in mathematics that could fit with this sort of stuff \endash  various forms of matrix analysis, various forms of graph theory and so on \endash 
 and there were big link ups with mathematicians, and social network interested people in the States, and I think that\rquote s where my work fitted in.  I actually had the details that they could then do various kinds }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8722711 of mathematical analysis with.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8744841 So one paper I wrote on the \lquote cell room\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196  for example \endash  early paper \endash  which I wrote for Mitchell\rquote 
s collected book on networks, I think that became pretty well a classic, actually.  So then very much used by mathematicians in the development of network procedures.  I then lost interest in it actually, I went into other things.  But I\rquote 
ve come back into it, simply because of the new shift in sociology, anthropology \endash  this movement of Bruno le Tour and all that stuff. I\rquote 
m critical of their work, because what Mitchell and co were doing, and the network people in the States, was trying to go beyond the idea 
of network as a metaphor, but trying to, in fact, redevelop it as a technique of looking at forms of social action which an institutional analysis would miss. So it\rquote s different from the le Tourian position.  In fact, the le Tourians \endash 
 because they\rquote re interested in that aspect \endash  should perhaps be looking at that other work that was going on, but I don\rquote 
t think they hit it off.  I know that the American lot, on networks, have no interest in the le Tourian stuff, yet they\rquote ve got the mathematisation and the approach, which may be very useful.  \tab But that\rquote s how I got into networks.  That
\rquote s why that early work was interesting to people.  I wrote a couple of other articles, but I never \'85 Now I\rquote m a little more interested in it, funnily enough.  I didn\rquote t have the theor
etical baggage to make it really interesting to me.  I tried to, in my first major book on this stuff, I tried to make that work, but I was dissatisfied with that too.  
