\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12404933 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1859212\charrsid1859212 Bruce:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 Yeah.  Of course, I\rquote 
m very keen on that idea.  I think the Rhodes Livingstone group, starting with Godfrey Wilson, who was the first Director, and then, I think, taking off even further with Max Gluckman, and then the later Directors- Elizabeth Coulson, Clyde-Mitchell 
\endash  the RLI was a really major institution, and all the more so when it was linked up as a research outfit for the Manchester Department, under Max.  The monographs that came out of the Rose Livingstone Institute, under Max, are classic 
still.  I think if you look at anthropology now, it\rquote s that group of monographs \endash  the most well-known would be by Vic Turner, I suppose, but Clyde\rquote s is always well-known, and Ian Cunneson, and Jaap van Volsen (?? \endash 
 33.04) and Bill Watts, and all these people, and Max\rquote s own work - a tremendous set of monographs came out, [which] I d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8744841 on\rquote 
t think have been equalled.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
The methodologies that Max set up have not been talked about much.  He used to insist that you had to file your notes in the Rose Livingstone Instit
ute library, and so you had your own copy, but there were copies also on display, which your colleagues could, in fact, look at, and you could check out }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12404933\charrsid10699196 each other\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
 work and so on, and that was also the possibility of the seminars where your work was plac
ed on the table and opened up to intensive discussion.  Max Gluckman had this notion that anthropology had to be a scientific discipline, scientific in the sense of history. The equivalent of the experiment, in history, was to be able to detail carefully 
your sources, and the sources determine the validity or not of the historical points that are being made, or the interpretations being made \endash  I think that\rquote s one way of looking at it.  Max\rquote 
s view was that you never knew what people did in their fieldwork, it
 could have been total fantasy as far as you know, but if they displayed their field notes and you had access to their field material, then it could be reanalysed, and you could actually reassess the quality of what it was that they had.  So in a sense, w
hat to do with field notes, and the kind of reanalysis that was possible was the anthropological equivalent of doing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12404933 rigorous experimental science.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 So that was the approach of the Rose Livingstone Institute.  Tremendously - I think you had to be a dictator
 to get that established, and Max was a kind of a dictator, a really benevolent despot, if I could put it that way!  And there were lots of reactions to him.  More than that, he was a tremendous guy though.  He was a generous and really a big intellect. B
ut I think, regardless of the sort of criticisms that would have been levelled at him, he actually established a fantastic Unit, and those monographs still continue. It was Max\rquote 
s creation at Manchester at the same time, I think that Manchester Group was significant.  I think it\rquote s never been the same since.  It\rquote s had good people in it, but it\rquote s ne}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12404933 ver been quite the same since.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
But then I think the same would go for Cambridge or Oxford, or LSE, it was a particular period in the history of anthropology, and th
ere were a number of really good schools who produced fabulous stuff. Probably better than now, in many ways, and because of the scientific model, I think, that influenced them all in one way or another, and the structure of funding \endash  that\rquote 
s my impression.  And the more they became dissipated and opened up, and you didn\rquote t have benevolent despots around, they became less systematic, and I think that\rquote s the case, actually.  
