.  And that, if you look at the Manchester monographs, that\rquote s how they worked. So they were interested in what happened, the nature of money economy, for example, in rural areas: that the rural areas, even though they were traditional
, were a re-invention within colonial capitalist conditions.  That was the structure they thought.  They didn\rquote 
t necessarily get it down too neatly, but that was their direction, and that was also their originality. Very different from the Americans, as I u
nderstand it, who saw urban as modern, rural as traditional, and they were interested in the movement from tradition to modernity.  That was not the argument from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, although they got misinterpreted in that way.  They were interested in how these were different possibilities within the same overarchin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11940673 g system.  Different position.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10699196\charrsid10699196 
So they were also against looking at traditional material if it was just pure exotic.  They couldn\rquote t see that - a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7940072 s Ben Mitchell used to call it \lquote 
